Title: Spatial Data Mining: Progress and Challenges Survey paper  
Author: Krzysztof Koperski Junas Adhikary Jiawei Han fkoperski, adhikary, 
Address: Burnaby, B.C., Canada V5A 1S6  
Affiliation: School of Computing Science Simon Fraser University  
Abstract: Spatial data mining, i.e., mining knowledge from large amounts of spatial data, is a highly demanding field because huge amounts of spatial data have been collected in various applications, ranging from remote sensing, to geographical information systems (GIS), computer cartography, environmental assessment and planning, etc. The collected data far exceeded human's ability to analyze. Recent studies on data mining have extended the scope of data mining from relational and transactional databases to spatial databases. This paper summarizes recent works on spatial data mining, from spatial data generalization, to spatial data clustering, mining spatial association rules, etc. It shows that spatial data mining is a promising field, with fruitful research results and many challenging issues. 
